The paper deals with information-theoretic security in a network setting, which suggests that it could belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) or Cryptography and Security (cs.CR) sub-categories. The fact that the network is connected and involves pairwise communication between nodes suggests that it could also belong to the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-category. The paper also mentions potential applications in cyber-physical systems and distributed-control systems, which suggests that it could belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category. Finally, the paper proposes practical and efficient schemes, which suggests that it could also belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category.
